\pard\b\f1\fs32 ABSTRACT\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The Optimized Retail Inventory Management System is a full-stack web application designed to improve the way retail stores manage stock, suppliers, purchases, sales, and dashboard-level inventory analysis. The project replaces manual, spreadsheet-based stock handling with a centralized browser-based solution that stores all operational records in MySQL and exposes them through a React frontend and an Express backend. The final implementation supports category management, supplier management, product creation, inline quantity editing, purchase entry, sales entry, low-stock alerts, overstock awareness, reorder suggestions, and recent stock movement analysis.\par\par
The project also demonstrates real deployment work. The frontend was deployed on Vercel, the backend on Render, and the MySQL database on Aiven. Deployment required cloud-oriented environment management, SSL-aware database connection handling, frontend-to-backend API routing, and configuration debugging. This report follows the style of the sample document you attached and presents the project in a full academic-report structure with descriptive sections, tables, and implementation-centered explanation.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 01  PROJECT OVERVIEW\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Project Title: Optimized Retail Inventory Management System Using Full-Stack Web Development.\par\par
The aim of this project is to create a practical retail inventory platform that allows store operators to manage products, suppliers, stock movement, and stock intelligence from a single digital dashboard. In many small and medium retail businesses, inventory is still maintained manually or through disconnected spreadsheet files. This leads to delays in stock updates, poor visibility into product movement, confusion about supplier relationships, and difficulty in identifying which products need replenishment.\par\par
The system built in this project addresses those challenges by centralizing all core inventory entities into a MySQL-backed data model and exposing them through a user-friendly interface. The application allows categories and suppliers to be created, products to be inserted, quantities to be modified directly from the product table, purchases and sales to be recorded, and stock analytics to be computed from actual transaction history. The result is a stronger, more accurate, and more understandable inventory workflow.\par\par
An additional refinement in the project was the move toward shared operational access. Rather than treating one user account as the only account that can manage stock, the final project direction is that all authenticated users should reach the same operational dashboard and be able to change stock values and transaction records.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 1.1  PROBLEM STATEMENT\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Retail inventory management becomes difficult when product records, supplier details, and movement logs are not connected in one system. A spreadsheet may show current stock, but it may not explain when stock was last updated or which purchase or sale caused the change. Supplier information may exist in another file or may be incomplete. This fragmentation leads to a high chance of inaccurate stock counts and poor reorder decisions.\par\par
The business risks are significant. If stock is lower than expected, customer orders may fail and sales opportunities are lost. If stock is higher than expected, money is tied up in slow-moving products. If supplier records are inconsistent, purchasing becomes inefficient and time-consuming. In short, the absence of a single digital workflow creates both operational and financial inefficiency.\par\par
The problem solved by this project is therefore clear: retail users need one connected inventory dashboard where they can manage categories, suppliers, products, quantity edits, purchases, sales, and stock analysis in one place. The Optimized Retail Inventory Management System was created to deliver exactly that solution.\par
