\pard\b\f1\fs30 1.4  END-TO-END SYSTEM WORKFLOW\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The system workflow begins when a user logs in or registers. After successful authentication, the frontend requests a bootstrap response from the backend. This response contains categories, suppliers, products, purchases, sales, dashboard summaries, alerts, and recent movement data.\par\par
Once the dashboard is loaded, the operator can work in three major ways. First, the operator can create or maintain master data such as categories and suppliers. Second, the operator can create products and edit their stock quantities. Third, the operator can record purchases and sales, which change stock movement and update analytics.\par\par
After every successful change, the dashboard refreshes and recalculates stock status and reorder guidance. This means the user always sees an up-to-date picture of inventory operations.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 02  REQUIREMENT ANALYSIS\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Requirement analysis focused on the actual information a retail business needs every day. The system must show what products exist, where they come from, how much stock is available, what recent purchases and sales occurred, and whether a product should be reordered soon. These needs shaped the structure of the application.\par\par
The frontend requirements emphasized simplicity and speed. The user should not need many pages to manage the store. Search, filtering, product creation, stock editing, and supplier management should be available in one main dashboard. The backend requirements emphasized validation, consistency, and reliable database integration.\par\par
Because the final application was also deployed online, deployment behavior became part of the requirement analysis too. The solution had to work correctly with frontend and backend separation, cloud database hosting, and secure configuration management.\par
\page
