\pard\b\f1\fs30 2.2  NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Usability was a major non-functional requirement. The dashboard needed to remain clear, readable, and visually organized despite supporting many operations in one page. This is why the application uses distinct cards, tables, panel headers, and colored action buttons.\par\par
Reliability was another important requirement. The backend should not continue silently when database configuration is broken. Instead, it should fail clearly at startup and allow troubleshooting through logs. This behavior became especially useful during deployment.\par\par
Maintainability was addressed by modular code organization. Frontend logic is separated into components and backend logic is separated into routes, controllers, store functions, and utility functions. This allowed the application to evolve without a complete rewrite.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 03  SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The project follows a layered architecture: presentation layer, application layer, and data layer. The presentation layer is the React frontend. The application layer is the Express backend. The data layer is the MySQL database.\par\par
The frontend communicates with the backend through REST-style JSON requests. The backend validates requests, processes business logic, and communicates with MySQL. The database stores operational records in normalized tables.\par\par
This design reduces coupling and supports easier debugging, better maintainability, and clearer project explanation in a report setting.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 3.1  FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The frontend is organized around the main App component, which controls authentication state, dashboard loading, form state, and UI feedback. Once authentication succeeds, the dashboard renders a complete set of components for operational work.\par\par
The most important interface areas are the statistics cards, reports panel, alerts panel, insights panel, categories panel, suppliers panel, products panel, and transactions panel. This breakdown makes the dashboard easy to explain and easy to extend.\par\par
The ProductsPanel is particularly important because it combines data listing and stock action in one place. This supports a realistic inventory workflow where speed matters.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 3.2  BACKEND ARCHITECTURE\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The backend is organized into route files, controller files, store files, and utility files. Authentication routes handle login and registration. Inventory routes handle category creation, supplier creation, product creation, quantity editing, purchase recording, sale recording, product deletion, and bootstrap loading.\par\par
Controllers handle request parsing and validation. Store functions handle SQL execution. Utility functions handle derived inventory calculations. This separation improves readability and keeps responsibilities clear.\par\par
Because the structure is modular, new rules or features can be added with less risk of breaking unrelated parts of the codebase.\par
