\pard\b\f1\fs30 3.4  DATABASE DESIGN\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The database schema uses six primary tables: users, categories, suppliers, products, purchases, and sales. Products reference categories and suppliers. Purchases reference products and suppliers. Sales reference products. This relational structure protects data consistency and supports reporting.\par\par
The products table is central to the project because it stores SKU, price, quantity, minimum stock, and maximum stock values. These fields are later used in stock status and reorder logic. Purchases and sales then provide the movement history that makes the analytics meaningful.\par\par
The role field in the users table remains in the schema because it was part of an earlier version, but the final project requirement is that all users should access the same inventory dashboard.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 04  IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Implementation started with the relational schema and seed data so the dashboard could be built and tested against real records. After database setup, the backend API was developed around route handlers and validation logic. The frontend then consumed those APIs and rendered the operational dashboard.\par\par
This staged approach helped reduce complexity during development. Instead of trying to build everything at once, each layer could be verified separately and then integrated. This also made deployment troubleshooting easier later because the team could reason about which layer was failing.\par\par
The implementation demonstrates not only feature completeness, but also the benefit of modular design in a full-stack academic project.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 4.1  AUTHENTICATION IMPLEMENTATION\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Registration accepts a name, email, and password. The backend checks that the fields are present, ensures the password is sufficiently long, normalizes the email, prevents duplicate email registration, and hashes the password before storing it.\par\par
Login validates the provided password against the stored password hash. If authentication succeeds, the backend returns a user object and token. The frontend uses that result to transition from the login page to the dashboard.\par\par
This authentication design is lightweight but sufficient for the project scope and supports both local and deployed execution.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 4.2  CATEGORY, SUPPLIER, AND PRODUCT IMPLEMENTATION\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Categories and suppliers were implemented first because product creation depends on them. Suppliers store identity and contact details, while categories group products logically. Product creation then combines the master data references with inventory-specific fields such as price, opening stock, minimum stock, and maximum stock.\par\par
The product creation flow includes backend validation for duplicate SKU values, missing references, invalid numbers, and impossible stock thresholds. This prevents data problems from spreading through the rest of the dashboard.\par\par
On the frontend, these forms are placed in visible dashboard panels so the user can create supporting data and products without leaving the main page.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 4.3  INLINE QUANTITY EDITING IMPLEMENTATION\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The quantity editor is one of the strongest practical features in the project. Instead of forcing users to open a dedicated edit screen, the products table lets them type a new quantity value directly and save or cancel the change from the same row.\par\par
This behavior is well suited to real store environments where quantity corrections are frequent. Physical stock counts, damaged goods, or receiving adjustments often require immediate correction. The inline editor supports this workflow naturally.\par\par
After a quantity update, the backend writes the change to the database and the dashboard refreshes, making the new stock status and reorder value visible at once.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 4.4  PURCHASES, SALES, AND MOVEMENT TRACKING\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Purchases and sales are the transactional backbone of the system. Purchase entries increase stock, while sales decrease stock. Each transaction is stored with date and pricing information, making it possible to build historical movement reporting and financial summaries.\par\par
The backend validates that a sale cannot exceed available stock. This protects against impossible negative quantities and keeps the data trustworthy. Purchases and sales are also enriched with readable product and supplier information for the dashboard.\par\par
Recent movement tracking merges both transaction types into one chronological list so the user can quickly see what changed most recently.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 05  STOCK ANALYTICS, ALERTS, AND REORDER RECOMMENDATIONS\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The analytical layer of the project is what makes it more than a basic stock register. For every product, the system computes stock value, status, estimated monthly sales, reorder point, and suggested reorder quantity. These are derived values, not fixed fields manually entered by the user.\par\par
The status logic compares quantity to min and max stock levels. The reorder logic takes into account recent sales, which makes it more useful than a static threshold alone. The stock value calculation gives a quick estimate of inventory worth using current quantity and price.\par\par
These calculations are then aggregated into dashboard cards, alerts, top-selling summaries, and reorder lists. This gives the operator actionable information rather than only raw records.\par
