\pard\b\f1\fs32 07  CLOUD DEPLOYMENT\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The completed project was deployed using three cloud services. Vercel hosts the frontend, Render hosts the Express backend, and Aiven hosts the MySQL database. This creates a production-style architecture in which each layer is responsible for one part of the system.\par\par
Cloud deployment required explicit environment variables. The backend required DB host, DB port, DB user, DB password, DB name, DB SSL mode, frontend URL, and port. The frontend required the backend API base URL. The cloud MySQL database required SSL support.\par\par
Once configured correctly, the deployment proved that the application works as a real online full-stack system.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs30 7.1  DEPLOYMENT ISSUES AND FIXES\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 The deployment process included several realistic issues: attempts to connect to localhost from the cloud, invalid or outdated Aiven host values, password mismatches, SSL requirements, incorrect database names, CORS errors, and frontend requests pointing to the wrong backend URL.\par\par
These were resolved through repeated inspection of Render logs, Vercel settings, Aiven connection details, and backend startup behavior. One important lesson was that deployment errors often come from configuration mismatches rather than code defects.\par\par
Documenting these fixes is valuable because it demonstrates that the project owner can not only build the system, but also operate and troubleshoot it in a deployed environment.\par
\page
\pard\b\f1\fs32 08  TESTING STRATEGY AND RESULTS\par\par
\b0\f0\fs24 Testing was performed at multiple levels. The first level was functional testing of application features: registration, login, categories, suppliers, product creation, quantity updates, purchases, sales, and deletion. The second level was validation testing for bad inputs and conflicting data. The third level was deployment testing for online execution.\par\par
Because the system handles live stock, validation testing was particularly important. The backend needed to prevent impossible sales, reject invalid numbers, and preserve uniqueness rules. These checks were confirmed through repeated manual tests.\par\par
Deployment testing verified that the backend could connect to Aiven MySQL, that the frontend could reach the backend API, and that the correct schema was being used in production.\par
